Here is an example of a PineScript code that provides buy and sell trailing stop orders based on the Wyckoff method:
```
// Define the input parameters
length = input(14, minval=1)

// Define the variables
sma = sma(close, length)
bought = 0
sold = 0

// Initialize the variables
buy = 0
sell = 0

// Buy order
if close > sma and not bought
    // Set the buy order
    buy = close
    bought = 1
    // Place a trailing stop sell order
    sell = buy + (length * atr(length))

// Sell order
if close < sma and not sold
    // Set the sell order
    sell = close
    sold = 1
    // Place a trailing stop buy order
    buy = sell - (length * atr(length))

// Plot the sell and buy orders
plot(sell, color=blue, linewidth=2, title="Trailing Stop Sell")
plot(buy, color=red, linewidth=2, title="Trailing Stop Buy")
```
This script uses the Simple Moving Average (SMA) indicator to identify the trend and the Wyckoff method to determine when to enter and exit the market. The script uses the Average True Range (ATR) indicator to determine the width of the trailing stop orders.

This script sets a buy order when the close price crosses above the SMA and resets the bought variable to 1. It then places a trailing stop sell order at a distance of (length \* atr(length)) from the last closed price.

Similarly, the script sets a sell order when the close price crosses below the SMA and resets the sold variable to 1. It then places a trailing stop buy order at a distance of (length \* atr(length)) from the last closed price.

It plots the sell orders in blue color and buy orders in red color.

Please keep in mind that this is just an example, and the actual code will depend on the specific requirements and needs of your trading strategy. Additionally, this script should be tested on historical data before using it in live trading.
